4.5.3 Resource URN Scheme
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

Each permission is linked to a resource identifier using the following URN scheme:

::

  urn:gauth:verb:<domain>:<action>              — Layer 1 core verbs
  urn:gauth:platform:<domain>:<permission>      — Layer 3 platform permissions

The resource URN is used by the policy evaluation engine (OPA/Cedar or equivalent) when evaluating access decisions. The engine maps the requested operation to a URN and checks the PoA's ``core_verbs`` and ``platform_permissions`` for the corresponding entry.

5. Extended Token Format — JWT Claims
=======================================

5.1 Overview
-------------

The JWT Extended Token is the OAuth/OIDC-native transport for PoA credentials. It is a signed JWT (JWS) conforming to RFC 7519 and RFC 7515. The claims are a projection of the canonical JSON Schema (Section 4) into JWT claim namespaces.

5.2 Header
-----------

.. code-block:: json

  {
    "alg": "RS256",
    "typ": "JWT",
    "kid": "ga_gov_cs_abc123"
  }

.. list-table::
   :header-rows: 1
   :widths: 15 15 30 40

   * - Claim
     - Required
     - Values
     - Description
   * - ``alg``
     - Yes
     - ``RS256`` (required), ``ES256`` (recommended)
     - Signing algorithm. ``HS256`` is prohibited (incompatible with multi-service trust)
   * - ``typ``
     - Yes
     - ``JWT``
     - Token type
   * - ``kid``
     - Yes
     - Key ID from JWKS
     - References the signing key

5.3 Standard Claims (RFC 7519)
-------------------------------

.. list-table::
   :header-rows: 1
   :widths: 10 10 10 70

   * - Claim
     - Type
     - Required
     - Description
   * - ``iss``
     - string
     - Yes
     - Issuer URI. Community: deployer's URI. Gimel-hosted: ``https://gauth.gimel.dev``
   * - ``sub``
     - string
     - Yes
     - Subject — the agent this token authorizes
   * - ``aud``
     - string[]
     - Yes
     - Audience — services authorized to accept this token
   * - ``exp``
     - number
     - Yes
     - Expiration (Unix timestamp)
   * - ``iat``
     - number
     - Yes
     - Issued-at (Unix timestamp)
   * - ``nbf``
     - number
     - Yes
     - Not-before (Unix timestamp). Typically equals ``iat``
   * - ``jti``
     - string
     - Yes
     - JWT ID. MUST be globally unique. Recommended format: ``tok_`` + UUIDv4 or equivalent high-entropy identifier. Implementations MAY use alternative formats provided global uniqueness is guaranteed (e.g., UUIDv7, ULID, or ``{issuer_prefix}_{random}``).

5.4 GAuth PoA Claims (``gauth`` namespace)
--------------------------------------------

The ``gauth`` namespace carries the PoA scope attributes from the canonical schema (Section 4). For agent mandates, the ``gauth`` and ``gauth_mandate`` namespaces represent two facets of the same credential: scope vs. operational state.

.. code-block:: json

  {
    "gauth": {
      "version": "0116.2.2",
      "credential_id": "poa-cs-001-abc123",
      "customer_id": "cust_123",
      "project_id": "proj_456",
      "scope": {
        "governance_profile": "enterprise",
        "active_modules": ["security-basics", "data-model-first"],
        "phase": "build",
        "allowed_paths": ["src/", "tests/"],
        "denied_paths": [".env", "secrets/"]
      },
      "scope_checksum": "sha256:a1b2c3d4...",
      "tool_permissions_hash": "sha256:4a5b6c7d...",
      "platform_permissions_hash": "sha256:1a2b3c4d...",
      "issued_by": "user_789",
      "approval_mode": "supervised"
    }
  }

5.5 Mandate Claims (``gauth_mandate`` namespace)
--------------------------------------------------

Present only when an agent mandate is active. Carries operational state for stateless validation.

.. code-block:: json

  {
    "gauth_mandate": {
      "mandate_id": "mdt_abc",
      "mandate_status": "active",
      "budget": {
        "total_cents": 10000,
        "remaining_cents": 4200
      },
      "session": {
        "session_id": "sess_xyz789",
        "remaining_tool_calls": 87,
        "max_lines_per_commit": 100,
        "started_at": "2026-03-26T10:00:00Z"
      },
      "agent_capability_hash": "sha256:9f8e7d6c5b4a..."
    }
  }

5.6 Token Size Budget
----------------------

.. list-table::
   :header-rows: 1
   :widths: 50 50

   * - Constraint
     - Limit
   * - GAuth Extended Token target
     - ≤ 4 KB encoded
   * - HTTP/2 SETTINGS_MAX_HEADER_LIST_SIZE
     - 16 KB
   * - nginx large_client_header_buffers default
     - 8 KB per header

The token carries hashes of large objects (``tool_permissions_hash``, ``platform_permissions_hash``) instead of the full objects. Full permission sets are resolved via stateful validation when needed. If a token would exceed 4 KB, the OAuth engine adapter MUST fail issuance.

6. W3C Verifiable Credential Representation
=============================================

6.1 PoA as Verifiable Credential
----------------------------------

The GAuth PoA credential is represented as a W3C Verifiable Credential conforming to the `W3C Verifiable Credentials Data Model v2.0 <https://www.w3.org/TR/vc-data-model-2.0/>`_. This representation enables:

* eIDAS 2.0 compatibility (EUDI wallet storage and presentation)
* Cryptographic verification without a proprietary verification service
* Interoperability with the broader SSI (Self-Sovereign Identity) ecosystem

