6.2.1 VC Snapshot and Mutable Fields
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

The W3C VC representation is a snapshot of the credential at issuance time. Budget fields (``totalCents``, ``remainingCents``) reflect the state at issuance and may become stale as the agent consumes budget. When a budget ceiling increase occurs (Section 10.3), a new W3C VC MUST be issued to reflect the updated budget. Verifiers using W3C VCs for budget validation SHOULD cross-reference the credential's ``id`` against the issuer's status list to confirm the credential has not been superseded.

6.3 JSON-LD Context
---------------------

The GAuth PoA JSON-LD context defines the vocabulary for PoA-specific terms. The full context definition is in Appendix A.

Context URI: ``https://gimelfoundation.com/contexts/poa/v2``

The context maps the canonical schema property names to JSON-LD terms, enabling RDF-compatible processing while maintaining human-readable property names.

6.4 DID Methods
-----------------

.. list-table::
   :header-rows: 1
   :widths: 20 15 30 35

   * - Entity
     - DID Method
     - Example
     - Rationale
   * - GAuth Service Endpoints
     - ``did:web``
     - ``did:web:gauth.gimel.dev``
     - DNS-verifiable, existing PKI, enterprise-friendly
   * - Agents (ephemeral)
     - ``did:key``
     - ``did:key:z6Mkf5rGMoatrSj1f4...``
     - Self-certifying, no registration needed, disposable
   * - Agents (persistent)
     - ``did:web``
     - ``did:web:foundry.gimel.dev:agents:opus-4.6``
     - For long-lived agent identities with discoverable DIDs

6.5 Credential Status — Revocation
------------------------------------

PoA revocation uses the `W3C Bitstring Status List v2.0 <https://www.w3.org/TR/vc-bitstring-status-list/>`_ specification:

* Each GAuth issuer maintains a status list credential at a well-known URL
* Each issued PoA credential is assigned a ``statusListIndex`` in the issuer's status list
* Revocation sets the corresponding bit to ``1``
* Verifiers check the status list before accepting a PoA credential
* Status lists are cached (recommended TTL: 5 minutes) to balance latency and revocation propagation speed

Revocation reasons (encoded in revocation metadata):

* ``agent_switch`` — agent being replaced
* ``session_end`` — session completed normally
* ``violation`` — mandate terms violated
* ``manual`` — human-initiated revocation
* ``budget_exceeded`` — budget fully consumed

6.6 Dual Transport Strategy
-----------------------------

.. list-table::
   :header-rows: 1
   :widths: 20 20 15 45

   * - Context
     - Transport
     - Format
     - Use Case
   * - OAuth/OIDC-native services
     - JWT Extended Token (Section 5)
     - JWS (signed JWT)
     - Service-to-service authorization, API access
   * - EUDI wallet
     - W3C VC (this section)
     - JSON-LD + Data Integrity Proof
     - Wallet storage, cross-domain presentation
   * - Selective disclosure
     - SD-JWT (Section 7.3)
     - SD-JWT
     - Privacy-preserving presentation
   * - Legacy REST
     - JWT in Authorization header
     - Bearer token
     - Backward-compatible API access

Both transports represent the same PoA credential (canonical schema), but with different fidelity. The JWT Extended Token carries scope metadata and permission hashes (for size constraints — see Section 5.6), requiring stateful lookup for full permission resolution. The W3C VC carries the complete credential subject including full ``coreVerbs`` and ``platformPermissions`` objects, enabling self-contained verification. The OAuth engine adapter issues both formats simultaneously when configured for dual-mode operation.

7. OpenID4VC Integration — Issuance, Presentation & Selective Disclosure
==========================================================================

7.1 OpenID4VCI — Credential Issuance
--------------------------------------

GAuth Authorization Servers issue PoA credentials via the `OpenID for Verifiable Credential Issuance (OpenID4VCI) <https://openid.net/specs/openid-4-verifiable-credential-issuance-1_0.html>`_ protocol. This enables standard wallets (including EUDI wallets) to receive GAuth PoA credentials.

7.1.1 Issuer Metadata
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

The GAuth AS exposes OpenID4VCI issuer metadata at ``{issuer}/.well-known/openid-credential-issuer``:

.. code-block:: json

  {
    "credential_issuer": "https://gauth.gimel.dev",
    "credential_endpoint": "https://gauth.gimel.dev/credentials",
    "credential_configurations_supported": {
      "GAuthPoACredential_jwt": {
        "format": "jwt_vc_json",
        "credential_definition": {
          "type": ["VerifiableCredential", "GAuthPoACredential"]
        },
        "cryptographic_binding_methods_supported": ["did:web", "did:key"],
        "credential_signing_alg_values_supported": ["ES256", "RS256"]
      },
      "GAuthPoACredential_sd_jwt": {
        "format": "vc+sd-jwt",
        "credential_definition": {
          "type": ["VerifiableCredential", "GAuthPoACredential"]
        },
        "cryptographic_binding_methods_supported": ["did:key"],
        "credential_signing_alg_values_supported": ["ES256"]
      }
    }
  }

7.1.2 Issuance Flow
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

::

  Agent / Wallet                              GAuth AS (Issuer)
        │                                           │
        │── Authorization Request ─────────→        │  (OAuth 2.0 / Pre-Authorized Code)
        │←── Authorization Response ────────        │
        │                                           │
        │── Token Request ─────────────────→        │
        │←── Access Token ─────────────────         │
        │                                           │
        │── Credential Request ────────────→        │  (POST /credentials)
        │   { format: "jwt_vc_json",                │
        │     types: ["GAuthPoACredential"],         │
        │     proof: { ... } }                      │
        │                                           │
        │←── Credential Response ──────────         │
        │   { credential: "eyJhbGci..." }           │

For machine-to-machine flows (agent mandate issuance), the **Pre-Authorized Code Flow** is used. The mandate issuer provides a pre-authorized code that the agent exchanges for its PoA credential without user interaction.

7.2 OpenID4VP — Credential Presentation
-----------------------------------------

Agents and wallets present PoA credentials to verifiers (services, PEP) via `OpenID for Verifiable Presentations (OpenID4VP) <https://openid.net/specs/openid-4-verifiable-presentations-1_0.html>`_.

7.2.1 Presentation Flow
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

::

  Agent / Wallet                                 Verifier (Service / PEP)
        │                                              │
        │←── Presentation Request ─────────            │
        │     { presentation_definition: {             │
        │          input_descriptors: [{               │
        │               constraints: {                 │
        │                 fields: [                    │
        │                   { path: "$.type",          │
        │                     filter: { const:         │
        │                       "GAuthPoACredential"   │
        │                     }}                       │
        │                 ]}                           │
        │          }]                                  │
        │     }}                                       │
        │                                              │
        │── Presentation Response ─────────→           │
        │     { vp_token: "eyJhbGci..." }              │
        │                                              │
        │←── Access Granted / Denied ──────            │

7.2.2 Presentation Definition
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

Verifiers request specific PoA attributes via Presentation Exchange. For example, a service that needs to verify governance profile and budget:

.. code-block:: json

  {
    "id": "gauth-poa-verification",
    "input_descriptors": [
      {
        "id": "poa-scope",
        "constraints": {
          "fields": [
            {
              "path": ["$.credentialSubject.scope.governanceProfile"],
              "filter": {
                "type": "string",
                "enum": ["enterprise", "strict", "behoerde"]
              }
            },
            {
              "path": ["$.credentialSubject.requirements.budget.remainingCents"],
              "filter": {
                "type": "integer",
                "minimum": 1
              }
            }
          ]
        }
      }
    ]
  }

7.3 SD-JWT — Selective Disclosure
----------------------------------

For privacy-preserving presentations, GAuth supports `SD-JWT (Selective Disclosure JWT) <https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/draft-ietf-oauth-selective-disclosure-jwt/>`_. This allows a PoA holder to disclose only the claims relevant to the verifier.

7.3.1 Disclosable Claims
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

.. list-table::
   :header-rows: 1
   :widths: 20 30 50

   * - Claim Group
     - Always Disclosed
     - Selectively Disclosable
   * - **Identity**
     - ``sub`` (agent ID)
     - ``customer_id``, ``project_id``, ``issued_by``
   * - **Scope**
     - ``governance_profile``, ``phase``
     - ``active_modules``, ``allowed_paths``, ``denied_paths``
   * - **Verbs**
     - —
     - Each individual verb permission
   * - **Platform**
     - —
     - Each individual platform permission
   * - **Budget**
     - —
     - ``total_cents``, ``remaining_cents``
   * - **Session**
     - ``session_id``
     - ``remaining_tool_calls``, ``max_lines_per_commit``

7.3.2 SD-JWT Example
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

An agent presenting to a service that only needs to verify governance profile and phase (not the full permission set):

Issuer-signed JWT (with undisclosed claims hashed):

::

  eyJhbGciOiJFUzI1NiJ9.eyJfc2QiOlsi...~
  WyJkcGtJQkVJNmgiLCJjdXN0b21lcl9pZCIsImN1c3RfMTIzIl0~
  WyI0Y0xYN3NiRjVwIiwicHJvamVjdF9pZCIsInByb2pfNDU2Il0

The verifier receives only the disclosed claims plus the SD-JWT signature. Non-disclosed claims are represented as hashes in the JWT — the verifier can confirm the JWT is validly signed without seeing the hidden claims.

7.4 JWKS and Key Discovery
----------------------------

GAuth issuers expose their public keys via two mechanisms:

.. list-table::
   :header-rows: 1
   :widths: 20 35 45

   * - Mechanism
     - Endpoint
     - Use Case
   * - JWKS (RFC 7517)
     - ``{issuer}/.well-known/jwks.json``
     - JWT token verification
   * - DID Document
     - ``did:web:{issuer-domain}`` → DID Document
     - W3C VC proof verification

Both mechanisms reference the same underlying key material. The ``kid`` in the JWT header corresponds to the ``id`` of the verification method in the DID Document.

8. OAuth Engine Integration
=============================

8.1 Adapter Interface Contract
-------------------------------

The OAuth Engine adapter is the Type A adapter in the GAuth architecture (see Section 9 for the adapter taxonomy). Any OAuth 2.1 / OIDC compliant authorization server can be integrated via this interface.

The adapter interface (language-agnostic):

::

  Interface: OAuthEngineAdapter

    issueToken(request: TokenIssuanceRequest) → TokenIssuanceResponse
      Inputs:  subject, audience[], ttl_seconds, poa_claims (from canonical schema)
      Outputs: signed_jwt, jti, kid, expires_at
      Errors:  INVALID_REQUEST, GOVERNANCE_REJECTED, TOKEN_TOO_LARGE

    introspectToken(token: string) → TokenIntrospectionResponse
      Inputs:  raw JWT string
      Outputs: active (boolean), claims (parsed), remaining_ttl
      Errors:  INVALID_TOKEN, EXPIRED, REVOKED

    revokeToken(jti: string, reason: RevocationReason) → void
      Inputs:  JWT ID, reason enum
      Outputs: (none)
      Errors:  TOKEN_NOT_FOUND

    getJWKS() → JSONWebKeySet
      Inputs:  (none)
      Outputs: JWKS with all active public keys
      Errors:  (none)

    rotateKey(options: KeyRotationOptions) → KeyRotationResult
      Inputs:  algorithm preference, old_kid (optional)
      Outputs: new_kid, rotation_timestamp
      Errors:  ROTATION_IN_PROGRESS

    issueVerifiableCredential(request: VCIssuanceRequest) → VCIssuanceResponse
      Inputs:  subject_did, poa_claims, format (jwt_vc_json | vc+sd-jwt)
      Outputs: verifiable_credential, credential_id
      Errors:  INVALID_REQUEST, UNSUPPORTED_FORMAT

8.1.1 Error Response Schema
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

All adapter methods that return errors MUST use the following standardized error response structure:

.. code-block:: json

  {
    "error": {
      "code": "GOVERNANCE_REJECTED",
      "message": "PoA issuance denied: governance profile 'behoerde' requires four-eyes approval",
      "details": {
        "field": "requirements.approval_mode",
        "expected": "four-eyes",
        "received": "autonomous"
      },
      "request_id": "req_abc123",
      "timestamp": "2026-03-26T10:00:00Z"
    }
  }

.. list-table::
   :header-rows: 1
   :widths: 20 10 10 60

   * - Field
     - Type
     - Required
     - Description
   * - ``error.code``
     - string
     - Yes
     - Error code from the adapter method's error enum
   * - ``error.message``
     - string
     - Yes
     - Human-readable error description
   * - ``error.details``
     - object
     - No
     - Structured details specific to the error type
   * - ``error.request_id``
     - string
     - No
     - Correlation ID for tracing
   * - ``error.timestamp``
     - string
     - No
     - ISO 8601 timestamp of the error

Error codes (complete registry):

.. list-table::
   :header-rows: 1
   :widths: 25 15 60

   * - Code
     - HTTP Status
     - Description
   * - ``INVALID_REQUEST``
     - 400
     - Malformed request or missing required fields
   * - ``GOVERNANCE_REJECTED``
     - 403
     - Policy evaluation denied the operation
   * - ``TOKEN_TOO_LARGE``
     - 413
     - Resulting token would exceed the 4 KB size budget
   * - ``INVALID_TOKEN``
     - 401
     - Token signature invalid or malformed
   * - ``EXPIRED``
     - 401
     - Token has expired (``exp`` < current time)
   * - ``REVOKED``
     - 401
     - Token has been revoked
   * - ``TOKEN_NOT_FOUND``
     - 404
     - Referenced JTI does not exist
   * - ``ROTATION_IN_PROGRESS``
     - 409
     - A key rotation is already in progress
   * - ``UNSUPPORTED_FORMAT``
     - 422
     - Requested credential format is not supported by this engine

8.2 OAuth Engine Comparison
-----------------------------

The GAuth OAuth Engine Adapter interface (Section 8.1) is designed to be engine-agnostic. Any OAuth 2.1 / OIDC-compliant authorization server that supports custom claims injection into access tokens can serve as a GAuth engine. Appendix D provides a non-normative comparison matrix of commonly used engines.

The reference implementation uses Ory Hydra (Section 8.3). Implementations MAY use any engine listed in Appendix D or any other compliant engine not listed.

8.3 Reference Implementation: Ory Hydra
-----------------------------------------

Hydra is the reference OAuth engine for GAuth due to its webhook-based token customization:

**Before Hook** — Called before token issuance. The GAuth runtime:

1. Validates the PoA request against the policy evaluation engine
2. Validates governance compliance (rule-based)
3. Returns ``allow: true/false`` to the OAuth engine

**After Hook** — Called after the engine generates the base JWT. The GAuth runtime:

1. Injects ``gauth`` and ``gauth_mandate`` claims
2. Computes and injects ``scope_checksum``
3. Returns the enriched claims to the engine for signing

9. Adapter Types
=================

9.1 Taxonomy
-------------

The GAuth architecture defines four adapter types. This specification (Apache 2.0) covers only Type A and Type B — the open interfaces that enable independent implementations.

.. list-table::
   :header-rows: 1
   :widths: 8 15 25 15 37

   * - Type
     - Name
     - Interface
     - License
     - Examples
   * - **A**
     - OAuth Engine
     - ``OAuthEngineAdapter`` (Section 8)
     - Open (Apache 2.0)
     - Ory Hydra, Keycloak, Auth0, Zitadel
   * - **B**
     - Exchangeable Module
     - Open interface (per module)
     - Open (Apache 2.0)
     - Foundry (code execution), Wallet (credential storage)
   * - **C**
     - Proprietary Extension
     - Proprietary
     - Gimel ToS
     - *(Outside scope of this specification)*
   * - **D**
     - Internal
     - Gimel-internal
     - Not applicable
     - *(Outside scope of this specification)*

9.2 Type A — OAuth Engine
---------------------------

The OAuth engine adapter has a fully open interface (Section 8). Any OAuth 2.1/OIDC-compliant authorization server can be plugged in.

9.3 Type B — Exchangeable Modules
-----------------------------------

Type B adapters provide open interfaces for services that users may swap with their own implementations. Reference implementations may be available from the Gimel platform. Implementations may also use any conformant third-party or self-hosted alternative.

* **Foundry (Code Execution Environment):** The foundry adapter provides the execution environment for agent operations. The open interface allows any compliant code execution environment to integrate with GAuth.
* **Wallet (Credential Storage):** The wallet adapter manages PoA credential storage and presentation. Compatible with EUDI wallets (Section 11) and other W3C VC-compliant wallet implementations.

9.4 Type C — Proprietary Extensions (Boundary)
------------------------------------------------

Type C adapters provide proprietary extensions beyond the open protocol. They are not part of this specification. Implementations that use Type C adapters operate under separate licensing terms (see Section 2).

9.5 Type D — Billing (Boundary)
---------------------------------

Type D adapters are internal to the Gimel platform and are not part of this specification.

10. Token Lifecycle
====================

10.1 Issuance Flow
-------------------

::

  Requesting Service                          GAuth Runtime
     │                                              │
     │── Mandate/PoA Issue Request ─────→           │
     │                                              │
     │         ┌────────────────────────────────────────┐
     │         │ 1. Validate request against PoA schema │
     │         │ 2. Evaluate policy (rule-based)        │
     │         │ 3. OAuth Engine Adapter: issue JWT     │
     │         │    (claims enrichment hook injects     │
     │         │     gauth claims from canonical schema)│
     │         │ 4. (Optional) Issue W3C VC in parallel │
     │         └────────────────────────────────────────┘
     │                                              │
     │←── { extended_token, vc (opt),               │
     │       scope_checksum, ... }                  │

10.2 Validation Modes
----------------------

10.2.1 Stateless Validation (Fast Path)
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

For read operations. Latency: <5ms.

1. Verify JWT signature against JWKS (``kid`` → public key)
2. Check ``exp`` / ``nbf`` / ``iat`` temporal validity
3. Check ``aud`` contains the validating service's URI
4. Verify ``scope_checksum`` matches recomputed checksum
5. Check ``governance_profile`` permits the operation
6. If ``gauth_mandate`` present, check ``mandate_status === "active"``

10.2.2 Stateful Validation (Full Path)
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

For write operations. Latency: ~50-100ms.

1. All stateless checks (10.2.1)
2. Mandate status lookup (active / revoked / expired / budget_exceeded / superseded)
3. Budget remaining > 0
4. ``gauth.tool_permissions_hash`` matches the hash computed from the stored mandate's tool permissions
5. Evaluate the specific operation against the full PoA using the policy engine

10.3 Renewal
-------------

Mandate scope is immutable — the capability set, governance profile, phase, paths, and approval mode cannot be changed after issuance. The only permitted in-session modification is a budget ceiling increase (additive-only), which triggers token re-issuance with updated budget claims. The previous token remains valid until its ``exp`` but carries stale budget data; verifiers using the stateful path (Section 10.2.2) will see the current budget from the mandate store. When operating in VC mode, a budget increase also requires re-issuance of the W3C VC (see Section 6.2.1).

